article.description:
Antawn Jamison scored 37 
points and Gilbert Arenas added 16 and nine assists as the
Golden State Warriors posted back-to-back wins for the first
time this season with a 100-90 victory over the Phoenix Suns.
article.headline: Jamison's 37 points lift Golden State
article.linkText: Jamison comes up big for Warriors against Suns
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Antawn Jamison is in his fourth straight season as the Golden State Warriors' leading scorer, yet he rarely demands the ball.
Jamison

When he did it on Saturday night against the Phoenix Suns -- and then played impressive defense in Golden State's 100-90 victory -- coach Eric Musselman knew the young Warriors had made another gradual step forward. Jamison matched his season-high with 37 points as the Warriors won consecutive games for the first time this season, holding off a late comeback by the Suns. Jamison was in the middle of it, playing like the franchise player the Warriors desperately hope he is. ''It's a big step,'' Musselman said. ''There was a point during the second quarter when Antawn grabbed a rebound and kind of mumbled under his breath, 'Give me the ball.' I told the team that Antawn asked for the ball, so we decided to put a little pressure on him at that point to deliver. Obviously, he did.'' Gilbert Arenas had 16 points, nine assists, seven rebounds and four steals as the Warriors overcame 25 turnovers and another big game by Stephon Marbury to snap their five-game losing streak against Phoenix. Phoenix trimmed a 17-point deficit to six on Casey Jacobsen's 3-pointer with 1:26 left, but Golden State held off the Suns with the type of late-game poise they've rarely shown during eight consecutive seasons out of the playoffs. ''Tonight, we made a dramatic step forward,'' Jamison said. ''We weren't content to just go back and forth, and then try to win it at the end. We got them down, and we didn't let anything throw us off.'' Golden State followed a road win over Denver on Friday night with its fourth victory in seven games. Jamison, whose offensive focus has wandered all season, shot his jumpers with confidence while leading all five starters in double figures. ''We thought I could do a good job exploiting some of their defensive weaknesses,'' Jamison said. ''I had some good opportunities against their defense.'' Marbury, who scored 43 points in a win over San Antonio one night earlier, had 32 against Golden State, but Phoenix shot less than 39 percent and made 23 turnovers while dropping to 1-5 on the road this season. Shawn Marion had 14 points and 14 rebounds for the Suns, whose three-game winning streak was snapped. ''We started making turnovers, and they were more aggressive than us,'' Marbury said. ''It doesn't matter what I did. We lost. It only matters when you win.'' The Warriors kicked off a five-game homestand with just their fifth victory over Phoenix in their last 28 meetings. Golden State moved into a three-way tie for last place in the Pacific Division with the Lakers and Clippers. Golden State broke open a close game with a 14-2 run in the third quarter led by Jamison, who scored 12 points in the quarter. Marbury kept the Suns in it single-handedly, scoring 15 points in the quarter from inside and outside. Jason Richardson beat the shot clock with a 3-pointer with 8:17 left, giving an 85-68 lead to Golden State. But the Warriors retreated into a defensive mode as rookies Jacobsen and Amare Stoudemire hit big shots, and Phoenix got within 94-88 before the Warriors put it away. With 40 seconds left, Arenas made a steal and threw a crosscourt pass to Richardson, who dunked for a 98-88 lead. ''The plays that we made allowed them to get going,'' Phoenix coach Frank Johnson said. ''We'd get in transition and turn it over. When we had the break, we just wouldn't make the right pass.'' Troy Murphy had 11 points, 13 rebounds and seven assists, and Erick Dampier added 11 points and nine rebounds. Stoudemire had 14 points and 11 rebounds. Game notes
Jacobsen, who played three years at nearby Stanford, scored seven points. All four of his shots from the field were 3-pointers. ... The officiating crew had a rough night, infuriating both teams with a series of questionable calls. Both head coaches got technical fouls in the second half. ... Golden State plays eight of its 13 December games at home.
